WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

2
00:01:39.300 --> 00:01:40.380
[IN ITALIAN] Prego.

3
00:01:47.130 --> 00:01:50.040
- Pronto.
- [ON PHONE] Is this Dr. Martins?

4
00:01:50.050 --> 00:01:51.380
Yes. this is Dr. Martins.

5
00:01:51.380 --> 00:01:53.920
- Who is this?
- NASA Space Biosciences Research.

6
00:01:53.920 --> 00:01:55.040
We're patching through your call.

7
00:01:55.050 --> 00:01:55.960
"My call"? I--

8
00:01:55.960 --> 00:01:58.540
Hello? Who is it now? Why can't I talk

9
00:01:58.540 --> 00:02:00.670
- to the same person?
- Hello. this is Dr. Martins.

10
00:02:00.670 --> 00:02:02.210
- Oh. please!
- Who is this?

11
00:02:02.210 --> 00:02:03.920
Something came out of your tank!

12
00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:05.420
Okay. slow down. Can you tell me

13
00:02:05.420 --> 00:02:07.090
- your name. please. sir?
- I told the man!

14
00:02:07.090 --> 00:02:09.630
I told them all!
Six times I've called already!

15
00:02:09.630 --> 00:02:12.460
Always a different person!
W-- Where am I calling now?

16
00:02:12.460 --> 00:02:15.590
Rome. I'm a research microbiologist
at Sapienza.

17
00:02:15.590 --> 00:02:17.920
- Oh. why'd they give me you?
- I--

18
00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:21.340
I consult for NASA sometimes.
epidemiological surveillance.

19
00:02:21.340 --> 00:02:23.420
Now it's your turn. Who are you. sir?

20
00:02:23.420 --> 00:02:24.920
Enos Minjarra.

21
00:02:25.710 --> 00:02:27.420
I live in Kiwirrkurra.

22
00:02:27.420 --> 00:02:28.710
Kiwirrkurra. where is that?

23
00:02:29.210 --> 00:02:30.750
We're dying!

24
00:02:30.750 --> 00:02:33.630
We're all dying!
Something came out of your tank!

25
00:02:33.630 --> 00:02:36.920
- What tank?
- The one uncle found. near Tanami Basin.

26
00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:40.670
- Australia?
- Yes. long time ago. in the '70s!

27
00:02:41.210 --> 00:02:42.540
But now. something came out.

28
00:02:42.540 --> 00:02:45.500
and if you're NASA. this is your tank!

29
00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:47.170
You have to help us!

30
00:02:47.920 --> 00:02:49.210
Where did the tank come from?

31
00:02:49.210 --> 00:02:51.090
Where did it come from...

32
00:02:51.090 --> 00:02:52.670
- Hello?
- Are you still there?

33
00:02:52.670 --> 00:02:53.840
- Hello...
- Sir...

34
00:02:53.840 --> 00:02:55.250
Taxi!

35
00:02:55.250 --> 00:02:56.840
Can you hear me. sir?

36
00:02:56.840 --> 00:02:58.960
I can't hear you.

37
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:05.420
Help us.

38
00:03:34.130 --> 00:03:37.170
Dr. Hero Martins. Major Robert Quinn.

39
00:03:37.920 --> 00:03:38.920
DTRA.

40
00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:42.670
This is my partner.
Lieutenant Colonel Trini Romano.

41
00:03:42.670 --> 00:03:44.670
How are ya?

42
00:03:44.670 --> 00:03:46.500
Where's the rest of your team?

43
00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:47.670
You're looking at us.

44
00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:52.050
Okay. let's get started.

45
00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:57.670
I thought the Skylab Space Station
fell in the Indian Ocean in '79.

46
00:03:57.670 --> 00:03:59.880
Well. most of it did.

47
00:03:59.880 --> 00:04:01.750
but when it broke up in the atmosphere.

48
00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:04.380
one of the O2 tanks
was recovered near here.

49
00:04:04.380 --> 00:04:06.500
Some guy found it.
put it in front of his house.

50
00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:08.210
thought people might pay to come see it.

51
00:04:08.210 --> 00:04:10.170
Just an empty oxygen tank?

52
00:04:10.170 --> 00:04:11.880
No. this one wasn't empty.

53
00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:13.960
It was sent up with a microbial organism.

54
00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:17.210
a parasitic fungus that could adapt
from one species to another.

55
00:04:17.210 --> 00:04:20.210
So. we sent up a terrestrial fungus
and it came back down.

56
00:04:20.210 --> 00:04:21.750
- What's the problem?
- The problem is.

57
00:04:21.750 --> 00:04:24.340
I think what went into the tank
is not what came out.

58
00:04:25.340 --> 00:04:28.630
And now. everyone in Kiwirrkurra is dying.
Or dead.

59
00:04:28.630 --> 00:04:30.960
No one has been in or out
since that phone call.

60
00:04:36.710 --> 00:04:38.540
- Epinephrine. yeah?
- Yeah.

61
00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:40.920
I would rather not discover
a lethal allergen the hard way.

62
00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:49.210
When were you first notified?
Less than 30 hours ago.

63
00:04:49.210 --> 00:04:51.880
- So. when did the outbreak start?
- That's unclear.

64
00:04:52.920 --> 00:04:54.880
Have you been called
for this sort of thing before?

65
00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:56.800
Space shit? Oh. all the time.

66
00:04:57.420 --> 00:04:59.540
Robert.
Sorry. No.

67
00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:02.130
Bioweapons and nuclear threats. yes.

68
00:05:02.130 --> 00:05:04.500
Extraterrestrials. meh. no.

69
00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:07.630
Why would they intentionally send
a hazardous organism into space?

70
00:05:07.630 --> 00:05:11.710
Research? To develop
an antifungal medication for astronauts.

71
00:05:12.340 --> 00:05:13.500
Switching bodycams on.

72
00:05:30.750 --> 00:05:32.000
A suitcase.

73
00:05:33.670 --> 00:05:36.170
- Somebody tried to leave.
- Or they arrived.

74
00:05:36.670 --> 00:05:39.960
Maybe people come from all over Australia
just to stay here.

75
00:05:39.960 --> 00:05:43.250
[OVER RADIO] ...and I am the light.

76
00:05:43.250 --> 00:05:47.000
He who believes in me shall rejoice.

77
00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:48.800
It shall be--

78
00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:56.210
Fourteen houses. 12 cars.
and no people.

79
00:05:57.460 --> 00:05:59.420
So. where the hell is everybody?

80
00:06:08.290 --> 00:06:11.090
I found it! Over here.

81
00:06:19.210 --> 00:06:20.800
Uh-huh.

82
00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:24.710
Here we go.

83
00:06:25.290 --> 00:06:26.920
We don't know
what we're dealing with.

84
00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:29.000
Don't touch the tank. Stay behind me.

85
00:06:41.340 --> 00:06:42.710
Huh.

86
00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:45.130
It's a folkloric solution.

87
00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:47.590
potatoes and dish soap.

88
00:06:47.590 --> 00:06:49.170
The guy must've been trying to clean it.

89
00:06:58.840 --> 00:07:01.170
Microfissures in the tank.

90
00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:05.380
polysaccharide in the potato.
sodium palmitate in the soap.

91
00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:07.170
Dripped into the tank. it's protein rich.

92
00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:09.790
The guy might not have meant to.

93
00:07:09.800 --> 00:07:11.790
but he created one hell
of a pro-growth environment.

94
00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:14.500
All it needs is some water
and it would really multiply.

95
00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:24.170
Who the hell are you?

96
00:07:29.710 --> 00:07:30.710
Hey. can you. um...

97
00:07:31.710 --> 00:07:33.170
just grab the loop in my suit?

98
00:07:34.460 --> 00:07:36.250
- I'm gonna pull against you.
- Yeah?

99
00:07:36.250 --> 00:07:37.540
But just don't let me go. okay?

100
00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:39.420
Yeah. I gotcha.

101
00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:41.460
All right. if I start to fall.
just pull back hard.

102
00:07:41.460 --> 00:07:42.460
Ready?

103
00:07:51.170 --> 00:07:53.460
Jesus Christ.

104
00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:57.040
- What is it?
- I don't know. But it's big. fast.

105
00:07:57.050 --> 00:07:58.840
and it's heterotrophic.

106
00:08:02.960 --> 00:08:04.880
- You okay?
- Yeah. thanks.

107
00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:07.250
Hey! I found a body!

108
00:08:33.090 --> 00:08:35.290
I've got you.
Thanks.

109
00:08:48.050 --> 00:08:51.210
Pockmarks in the skin. erupted flesh.

110
00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:53.050
uh...

111
00:08:54.590 --> 00:08:55.920
he... he burst.

112
00:08:56.750 --> 00:08:57.750
You don't say.

113
00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:00.170
Plates of the skull are split.

114
00:09:00.170 --> 00:09:02.050
all eight seamlines.

115
00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:07.460
Oh. my God.
What?

116
00:09:09.710 --> 00:09:11.250
It's all of them.

117
00:09:21.800 --> 00:09:24.130
Why the hell they all climb their roofs?

118
00:09:24.130 --> 00:09:26.380
It told them to.
The fungus?

119
00:09:26.380 --> 00:09:30.000
Yes. That's how an insect-pathogenic
fungus reproduces.

120
00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:34.000
It controls all brain function.
movement. reflex. impulse.

121
00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.290
It's driven to infect other hosts
any way it can.

122
00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:40.960
Sometimes. it tells them
to climb and wait.

123
00:09:40.960 --> 00:09:43.130
- For what?
- For the fungus to overfill

124
00:09:43.130 --> 00:09:45.800
its body cavity and burst.

125
00:09:46.590 --> 00:09:47.670
And spread.

126
00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:49.920
But that's... that's only insects.

127
00:09:51.630 --> 00:09:52.880
It was.

128
00:09:55.590 --> 00:09:57.090
Jesus!

129
00:09:59.630 --> 00:10:02.130
Get your sample. Doc.
and let's get the hell out of here.

130
00:10:03.750 --> 00:10:05.840
Maybe the tank
picked up a hitchhiker.

131
00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:08.540
maybe a spore penetrated
its shell upon reentry.

132
00:10:08.540 --> 00:10:11.420
but... however it happened.

133
00:10:12.340 --> 00:10:14.380
I think we've created a new species.

134
00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:19.790
We need to burn this place.
To the ground. Right away.

135
00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:23.090
A couple M47s loaded with
white phosphorus ought to do the job.

136
00:10:23.090 --> 00:10:25.340
Yeah.
That will cover any spread.

137
00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:39.130
Dr. Martins.

138
00:10:39.710 --> 00:10:40.710
Dr. Martins?

139
00:10:41.460 --> 00:10:42.460
Come on. we need to go.

140
00:10:43.340 --> 00:10:44.590
All right. I'm done.

141
00:10:49.710 --> 00:10:50.800
Come on. let's move.

142
00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:01.750
You smell that? Burnt toast?

143
00:11:01.750 --> 00:11:04.250
In your suit?
It's not possible.

144
00:11:04.250 --> 00:11:06.750
My suit is sealed and overpressured.
there's nothing in here

145
00:11:06.750 --> 00:11:08.290
but oxygen and clean CO2.

146
00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:10.960
Feel anything?

147
00:11:13.170 --> 00:11:15.590
- A little hot.
- We'll lose the suits at the jeep.

148
00:11:15.590 --> 00:11:18.460
They need to burn here anyway.
We'll check yours for breaches.

149
00:11:19.090 --> 00:11:22.040
Who the hell's gonna store this thing?
CDC?

150
00:11:22.040 --> 00:11:26.090
No. Atlanta and Galveston
will both classify extraterrestrial.

151
00:11:26.090 --> 00:11:27.250
They'll reject it outright.

152
00:11:28.090 --> 00:11:29.960
Fort Detrick?

153
00:11:29.960 --> 00:11:32.460
Still in a top-down review
after their last breach.

154
00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:33.880
I wouldn't trust it to them.

155
00:11:37.920 --> 00:11:39.250
What about Atchison?

156
00:11:40.130 --> 00:11:41.630
What. the mines in Kansas?

157
00:11:41.630 --> 00:11:44.170
Exactly. nobody ever uses them.

158
00:11:45.130 --> 00:11:46.290
Yeah. not bad.

159
00:11:47.250 --> 00:11:48.710
No. No!

160
00:11:49.420 --> 00:11:51.420
Hero? You okay?

161
00:11:51.420 --> 00:11:53.250
Stop! Stop!

162
00:11:53.250 --> 00:11:54.500
Can you hear me?

163
00:12:06.880 --> 00:12:09.750
Spread. spread. spread. spread.

164
00:12:09.750 --> 00:12:11.290
spread. spread. spread!

165
00:12:13.960 --> 00:12:15.840
Hero. can you hear me?

166
00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:18.090
She's infected! Stop!

167
00:12:19.250 --> 00:12:20.250
Stop!

168
00:12:21.290 --> 00:12:22.290
Stop!

169
00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:30.290
I can't move my legs.

170
00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.540
Hero! Stop!

171
00:12:33.540 --> 00:12:34.880
Stop!

172
00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:38.960
Hero. no! Listen to me! Stop.

173
00:12:43.540 --> 00:12:46.040
Hero. don't! Don't! What are you--

174
00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:48.460
No. Hero. Stop.

175
00:12:48.460 --> 00:12:49.710
Put it down. Hero.

176
00:12:49.710 --> 00:12:51.340
Hero. you're infected!

177
00:12:52.750 --> 00:12:54.670
Don't! No. no. no. no!

178
00:12:59.040 --> 00:13:00.750
Oh. God.

179
00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:04.090
Robert.

180
00:13:04.090 --> 00:13:05.090
Robert!

181
00:15:48.540 --> 00:15:51.540
[ON TAPE] Making the decision
to change your life

182
00:15:52.170 --> 00:15:54.210
is a courageous first step.

183
00:15:55.380 --> 00:15:58.880
Once you're convinced
of the need for change.

184
00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:02.920
some of that courage will need
to be directed outward

185
00:16:02.920 --> 00:16:06.920
into a world that would prefer
you stay exactly as you are.

186
00:16:08.670 --> 00:16:12.250
Dealing with difficult
and confrontational people

187
00:16:12.250 --> 00:16:14.790
is. like many things. a skill

188
00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:17.670
that can be developed over time.

189
00:16:17.670 --> 00:16:21.460
but no change is possible without--

190
00:16:25.840 --> 00:16:27.630
Well. shithead?

191
00:16:29.210 --> 00:16:31.960
I told you. Griffin. can't help you.

192
00:16:31.960 --> 00:16:34.710
I wish I could. but I can't. Sorry.

193
00:16:34.710 --> 00:16:37.460
I knew you were stupid.
didn't think you were that stupid.

194
00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:40.090
I'm not stupid.

195
00:16:40.090 --> 00:16:42.130
I mean. I-- Listen.
I get you're my boss and all.

196
00:16:42.130 --> 00:16:43.380
and I would help you if I could.

197
00:16:43.380 --> 00:16:45.460
but it's messed up for me...

198
00:16:45.460 --> 00:16:48.290
...vis-à-vis my. you know.
personal situation.

199
00:16:48.290 --> 00:16:50.340
and I'm not gonna do it.

200
00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:51.790
Okay. so you think about it.

201
00:16:52.420 --> 00:16:54.040
No. I wish I didn't even know about it.

202
00:16:54.040 --> 00:16:55.960
What's the big goddamn deal?
Nobody's gonna know!

203
00:16:58.540 --> 00:17:00.420
I've heard those words before.

204
00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:04.460
- You do it.
- I don't work nights.

205
00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:06.630
and no one's gonna come
for that shit in the daytime.

206
00:17:06.630 --> 00:17:07.920
- Well.
- So. just let 'em in

207
00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:09.250
so you and me don't have a problem.

208
00:17:09.250 --> 00:17:11.250
Why do we gotta have a problem?

209
00:17:11.250 --> 00:17:14.040
'Cause you know. but you're not in.

210
00:17:14.040 --> 00:17:16.790
and if you're not in and you know.

211
00:17:17.420 --> 00:17:18.750
then we got a problem.

212
00:17:23.170 --> 00:17:24.790
You got the new help tonight.

213
00:17:24.790 --> 00:17:27.090
She's on walk and lock check till 12:00.

214
00:17:27.840 --> 00:17:28.840
What's her name?

215
00:17:29.960 --> 00:17:31.670
Don't get any ideas.

216
00:17:31.670 --> 00:17:33.210
She's already hitting on me.

217
00:17:34.090 --> 00:17:35.590
Ugh.

218
00:17:37.840 --> 00:17:40.250
Something's beeping in there!
Fix it!

219
00:17:40.250 --> 00:17:42.090
Wait. wha--

220
00:17:43.750 --> 00:17:45.000
Asshole.

221
00:18:21.790 --> 00:18:23.380
...expect heavy rains tonight

222
00:18:23.380 --> 00:18:26.580
with showers starting in the early evening
and intensifying overnight.

223
00:18:26.590 --> 00:18:29.040
Thunderstorms are likely
with strong gusts of wind

224
00:18:29.040 --> 00:18:30.210
and potential local--

225
00:18:38.090 --> 00:18:41.250
Ah. Mrs. Rooney. how's it going?
Staying cool?

226
00:18:41.250 --> 00:18:44.460
I need to get into SB-114.

227
00:18:45.090 --> 00:18:46.710
It's my anniversary.

228
00:18:47.500 --> 00:18:49.540
Ah. okay. Superhot out. right?

229
00:18:49.540 --> 00:18:51.920
Kinda weird this time of year.
but I guess we gotta--

230
00:18:51.920 --> 00:18:53.590
I need to get into it quick.

231
00:18:54.380 --> 00:18:57.710
God. absolutely. Storage emergency.
I totally get it.

232
00:18:57.710 --> 00:18:59.290
It's snowing. it's sunny.

233
00:18:59.290 --> 00:19:01.460
it's raining. it's hot. I... I don't know.

234
00:19:01.460 --> 00:19:03.380
but guess we gotta get used to it.
you know?

235
00:19:03.380 --> 00:19:05.880
- Global warming--
- Could you stop talking?

236
00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:07.210
Yeah.

237
00:19:07.210 --> 00:19:09.420
Please. let me get the elevator for you.
Just one sec.

238
00:19:12.290 --> 00:19:14.090
All right there. Mrs. Rooney.

239
00:19:14.090 --> 00:19:16.830
Uh. well. try not to get lost down there.
It can be pretty confusing.

240
00:19:16.840 --> 00:19:18.880
I mean. even for me.
and I'm here every day.

241
00:19:18.880 --> 00:19:20.750
- Going down.
- Keep an eye on you!

242
00:19:20.750 --> 00:19:22.340
Fifty-two years...

243
00:19:35.040 --> 00:19:35.960
Hmm.

244
00:19:35.960 --> 00:19:37.380
Sub-level one.

245
00:20:22.340 --> 00:20:24.000
Happy anniversary.

246
00:20:32.250 --> 00:20:33.250
Okay.

247
00:20:47.840 --> 00:20:48.960
Maybe...

248
00:20:53.210 --> 00:20:54.540
Maybe. first...

249
00:20:55.750 --> 00:20:56.840
we'll have a nap.

250
00:21:04.670 --> 00:21:06.920
Feeling unhappy. stressed.

251
00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:09.210
and exhausted as a result

252
00:21:09.210 --> 00:21:11.040
of constantly putting...

253
00:21:11.040 --> 00:21:13.630
...other people's priorities
ahead of yours...

254
00:21:24.250 --> 00:21:26.840
Huh...

255
00:21:42.540 --> 00:21:44.790
S-- Sorry. Hello.

256
00:21:44.790 --> 00:21:48.040
Uh. c-- can I get your opinion
on something? Real quick?

257
00:21:49.540 --> 00:21:50.750
Sorry again.

258
00:21:53.630 --> 00:21:55.880
So. what? You just started
picking up shifts this week

259
00:21:55.880 --> 00:21:57.130
or--

260
00:21:58.250 --> 00:21:59.250
Sorry.

261
00:22:02.750 --> 00:22:04.630
Yeah. it's a pretty shit job.
you know.

262
00:22:04.630 --> 00:22:06.460
but whatever.

263
00:22:07.630 --> 00:22:09.460
Discount on storage.

264
00:22:10.750 --> 00:22:12.460
I got a lot of thoughts on that though.

265
00:22:12.460 --> 00:22:13.670
Basically. don't do it.

266
00:22:13.670 --> 00:22:16.290
Hanging onto all your shit forever?

267
00:22:16.290 --> 00:22:18.130
It's a really terrible idea.

268
00:22:19.460 --> 00:22:22.090
This whole industry is a racket.
It's like crack.

269
00:22:22.750 --> 00:22:25.040
You just keep piling more
and more shit in there.

270
00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:26.960
and pretty soon.
you can't throw anything out--

271
00:22:26.960 --> 00:22:28.420
I don't hear anything.

272
00:22:28.420 --> 00:22:29.630
Well. I definitely heard it.

273
00:22:30.250 --> 00:22:32.000
Well. not definitely. I mean. I was. like.

274
00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.250
I don't know. aware of it.
you know what I mean?

275
00:22:34.250 --> 00:22:36.340
Like. I was having an argument
with my brain about it.

276
00:22:37.250 --> 00:22:38.790
Does... does that ever happen to you?

277
00:22:39.880 --> 00:22:41.830
You are very chatty.

278
00:22:41.840 --> 00:22:42.920
Uh. yeah. I know.

279
00:22:43.670 --> 00:22:45.210
- It can be a problem.
- Mmm.

280
00:22:47.840 --> 00:22:51.580
- I'm Teacake.
- Hmm. "Teacake."

281
00:22:51.590 --> 00:22:53.090
You must have loved that book.

282
00:22:54.210 --> 00:22:55.290
What book?

283
00:22:55.290 --> 00:22:57.830
You're named after
a famous character from a book.

284
00:22:57.840 --> 00:22:59.580
Oh.

285
00:22:59.590 --> 00:23:00.670
No. that ain't it.

286
00:23:02.130 --> 00:23:04.540
Long story. Fairly annoying.

287
00:23:04.540 --> 00:23:06.630
Oh.

288
00:23:13.130 --> 00:23:14.210
What?

289
00:23:16.500 --> 00:23:19.000
I said I do not want to hear it.

290
00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:21.670
- Listen. I've got a problem--
- Yeah. well. you always have a problem.

291
00:23:22.750 --> 00:23:24.130
- I've gotta go.
- Don't hang up on--

292
00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:31.380
Long story. Fairly annoying.

293
00:23:31.380 --> 00:23:32.460
Yeah.

294
00:23:33.380 --> 00:23:34.540
I'm Naomi.

295
00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:38.630
Nice to meet you.

296
00:23:45.130 --> 00:23:47.380
- See what I'm saying?
- Yeah.

297
00:24:07.340 --> 00:24:10.830
Hello? Hello?

298
00:24:10.840 --> 00:24:13.630
[ON PHONE] I'm calling about
the 1978 Plymouth Duster for sale.

299
00:24:17.630 --> 00:24:20.000
- Are you there?
- Give me five minutes.

300
00:24:25.090 --> 00:24:28.040
- Who was that?
- My other wife.

301
00:24:28.040 --> 00:24:30.670
How can you be funny right away
in the middle of the night?

302
00:24:30.670 --> 00:24:31.750
It's a gift.

303
00:24:32.880 --> 00:24:36.170
- One of the kids?
- No. new voice.

304
00:24:36.170 --> 00:24:37.420
I'm sure it's nothing.

305
00:24:37.420 --> 00:24:39.460
Somebody having a panic attack.

306
00:24:40.790 --> 00:24:41.920
Get back to sleep.

307
00:24:52.630 --> 00:24:54.040
You wanna call Griffin?

308
00:24:54.040 --> 00:24:56.500
Under no circumstance
do I wanna call Griffin.

309
00:24:58.960 --> 00:25:00.290
He tried that shit on you already?

310
00:25:01.420 --> 00:25:03.130
He's a pig. Pigs do.

311
00:25:03.130 --> 00:25:05.630
Damn. call the office. Get his ass fired.

312
00:25:05.630 --> 00:25:08.540
Mmm. It won't play out that way.
and I need the job.

313
00:25:08.540 --> 00:25:10.630
He ask you to flip those TVs
he racked yet?

314
00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:13.500
That has not come up.

315
00:25:13.500 --> 00:25:14.880
Oh. it will. Trust me.

316
00:25:15.630 --> 00:25:19.380
He's got. like. a million of 'em stashed
in a couple units. up there. downstairs.

317
00:25:20.460 --> 00:25:22.090
That.

318
00:25:27.130 --> 00:25:29.170
Oh.

319
00:25:29.790 --> 00:25:31.540
- It's coming from inside the wall.
- Yeah.

320
00:25:35.710 --> 00:25:37.040
Huh.

321
00:25:39.090 --> 00:25:40.460
What do you wanna do about it?

322
00:25:40.460 --> 00:25:43.830
What I wanna do
is take this picture down.

323
00:25:43.840 --> 00:25:46.000
go to the tool closet.
grab a claw bar.

324
00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.290
smash a hole through
this cheap-ass gypsum Sheetrock.

325
00:25:48.290 --> 00:25:49.710
and see what's beeping back there.

326
00:25:49.710 --> 00:25:51.130
Well. I'm okay with that if you are.

327
00:25:51.130 --> 00:25:52.500
W-- I said that's what I wanna do.

328
00:25:52.500 --> 00:25:54.500
- not what I'm gonna do.
- Oh. come on. we can. uh...

329
00:25:54.500 --> 00:25:57.290
We can hang the picture back up
over the hole to cover it.

330
00:25:57.290 --> 00:25:59.330
bring in a piece of Sheetrock tomorrow.

331
00:25:59.340 --> 00:26:01.880
I'm handy. I can help you patch it up.
nobody'll know the difference.

332
00:26:01.880 --> 00:26:05.040
- Why would we do that?
- I have a very curious nature.

333
00:26:05.040 --> 00:26:06.920
Clearly. No. I don't think so.

334
00:26:11.040 --> 00:26:12.090
It's my. uh...

335
00:26:13.130 --> 00:26:14.380
kid's dad.

336
00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:16.000
Oh.

337
00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:18.420
High school. Shit happens.

338
00:26:19.040 --> 00:26:20.540
Yeah. That it does.

339
00:26:22.290 --> 00:26:24.710
He is a hopeless man-child.

340
00:26:24.710 --> 00:26:28.500
and that sort of shit
makes me wanna smash through walls.

341
00:26:28.500 --> 00:26:31.250
- Let's. let's do it.
- So we can see a dead smoke alarm?

342
00:26:31.250 --> 00:26:34.540
- I don't think so.
- Maybe it's a smoke alarm.

343
00:26:35.340 --> 00:26:38.000
but maybe it's something terrible.

344
00:26:38.630 --> 00:26:41.290
I mean. we're guards. right?
We're supposed to guard the place.

345
00:26:41.290 --> 00:26:43.830
Yeah. You know. I need this job too.

346
00:26:43.840 --> 00:26:45.500
You're not gonna lose it.

347
00:26:45.500 --> 00:26:48.210
No. you don't understand.
Like. I have to have this job.

348
00:26:48.210 --> 00:26:49.500
I get it.

349
00:26:49.500 --> 00:26:52.000
No. you don't.
I mean. it's like a condition.

350
00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:54.960
I said I get it.
I've lived here all my life.

351
00:26:55.750 --> 00:26:57.080
I know what a parole condition is.

352
00:26:57.090 --> 00:27:01.250
and I know where black-and-gray tattoos
with shitty ballpoint ink get done.

353
00:27:01.920 --> 00:27:03.340
Ellsworth. right?

354
00:27:04.340 --> 00:27:05.840
I mean. I'm hoping it was Ellsworth.

355
00:27:06.920 --> 00:27:08.250
Yeah. it was.

356
00:27:08.250 --> 00:27:10.380
Great! So. you're not violent.

357
00:27:10.380 --> 00:27:14.790
Now. will you go and get the claw bar
and smash through that wall for me?

358
00:27:17.790 --> 00:27:18.880
Please?

359
00:27:46.420 --> 00:27:50.670
- [ON PHONE] Go ahead.
- 0474. Blue indigo. What's up?

360
00:27:50.670 --> 00:27:53.380
We're getting a temperature-breach alert
from a decommissioned facility

361
00:27:53.380 --> 00:27:55.460
in the Atchison mines
in eastern Kansas.

362
00:27:57.460 --> 00:28:00.750
Yeah. I wondered about that.
given the weather changes.

363
00:28:00.750 --> 00:28:04.960
I wrote a memo in 2007
on that very subject.

364
00:28:04.960 --> 00:28:06.790
I don't see it in the file.

365
00:28:06.790 --> 00:28:09.290
And I called about five years after that.

366
00:28:09.290 --> 00:28:12.750
And again two years ago.
What time did the alert come in?

367
00:28:12.750 --> 00:28:16.630
- 3:14 p.m. Central Standard Time.
- And you're just calling me now?

368
00:28:16.630 --> 00:28:18.340
It took some time
to figure out who to call.

369
00:28:20.540 --> 00:28:23.830
Okay. I'm 73 miles from Seymour Johnson.

370
00:28:23.840 --> 00:28:25.630
I can be there in 90 minutes.

371
00:28:25.630 --> 00:28:27.580
I need a plane from there

372
00:28:27.590 --> 00:28:29.830
and a car waiting on the other end.

373
00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:32.500
Is it your opinion
this qualifies as a Heightened Threat?

374
00:28:32.500 --> 00:28:37.420
My opinion is it qualified
as an Exceptional Threat at 3:14 p.m.

375
00:28:37.420 --> 00:28:38.580
I'll see what I can do about--

376
00:28:38.590 --> 00:28:39.840
I'm not finished.

377
00:28:40.750 --> 00:28:43.580
I don't have any equipment.
I need everything on the list.

378
00:28:43.590 --> 00:28:45.500
I'm sorry. Mr. Quinn.

379
00:28:45.500 --> 00:28:49.460
- I'm just not familiar with--
- I wrote an ECI white paper in 2009.

380
00:28:49.460 --> 00:28:52.670
It's compartmented
and stored in a clean vault.

381
00:28:53.250 --> 00:28:56.630
Read the report
and have everything listed in Appendix A

382
00:28:56.630 --> 00:29:00.500
in the car in Kansas when I land.
Understood?

383
00:29:00.500 --> 00:29:03.000
I can't do all that
without multiple authorizations.

384
00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:06.380
Listen to me.
This fungus is intensely adaptable.

385
00:29:06.380 --> 00:29:09.580
It will mutate and spread
in unpredictable ways.

386
00:29:09.590 --> 00:29:12.580
Get Gordon Gray to clear you.
Only Gordon Gray.

387
00:29:12.590 --> 00:29:14.040
Don't call anyone else.

388
00:29:16.210 --> 00:29:17.580
What's your name?

389
00:29:17.590 --> 00:29:20.170
You know we can't give that kind
of information out over the phone.

390
00:29:20.170 --> 00:29:22.630
Just your first one. even a fake one.

391
00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:25.130
something to call you.

392
00:29:26.590 --> 00:29:27.750
Abigail.

393
00:29:27.750 --> 00:29:29.000
Okay. Abigail.

394
00:29:30.170 --> 00:29:32.340
Remember those good grades
you got in high school?

395
00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.040
And the sports
you trained your ass off for?

396
00:29:35.840 --> 00:29:37.750
The college you fought to get into?

397
00:29:38.750 --> 00:29:42.500
Remember the abuse you put up with
your first year in the department?

398
00:29:43.210 --> 00:29:46.340
And the personal life you've given up
for the last. I don't know.

399
00:29:46.960 --> 00:29:50.420
from your voice. it sounds
like maybe ten. 12 years now?

400
00:29:51.130 --> 00:29:54.500
- Nine.
- Nine. All those sacrifices.

401
00:29:54.500 --> 00:29:57.380
all the shit you've had to eat
because you wanted to do

402
00:29:57.380 --> 00:29:58.880
what was right for your country.

403
00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:01.170
This is what it was for.

404
00:30:02.130 --> 00:30:04.130
It's worse than you can possibly imagine.

405
00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:07.960
We are at Pucker Factor Ten. Abigail.

406
00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:11.090
But you and I are gonna sort this shit.

407
00:30:12.090 --> 00:30:13.170
Sounds good?

408
00:30:15.540 --> 00:30:16.540
Yes.

409
00:30:17.630 --> 00:30:19.830
- Yes. sir.
- Get the stuff on the list.

410
00:30:20.830 --> 00:30:22.630
I'll be at Seymour in 90 minutes.

411
00:30:28.710 --> 00:30:30.210
A whole bunch of stuff back here.

412
00:30:33.540 --> 00:30:34.540
Sorry.

413
00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:39.000
What's that say?
I gotta get a closer look.

414
00:30:40.250 --> 00:30:41.250
Sorry.

415
00:30:44.960 --> 00:30:46.170
Huh.

416
00:30:46.170 --> 00:30:49.090
"NTC. Thermistor Breach."

417
00:30:50.090 --> 00:30:52.040
Huh. Hold on. give me a second.

418
00:30:54.630 --> 00:30:55.960
Oh. my God! Are you okay?

419
00:30:56.500 --> 00:30:58.750
Yep! Planned that.

420
00:30:59.710 --> 00:31:01.130
Whoa.

421
00:31:05.830 --> 00:31:08.500
"Airtight Integrity." yeah.

422
00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:11.340
"plus or minus 0.1 degree Celsius."

423
00:31:12.960 --> 00:31:15.830
"Cold Chain Synchronicity."
Jesus. there's. like. 20 of them.

424
00:31:17.090 --> 00:31:18.670
But that's the only one that's blinking.

425
00:31:18.670 --> 00:31:22.250
- "NTC. Thermistor Breach."
- What's it do?

426
00:31:22.250 --> 00:31:25.130
Well. a thermistor is part
of an electrical circuit.

427
00:31:25.130 --> 00:31:27.830
There are two kinds. the positive kind

428
00:31:27.830 --> 00:31:29.580
where resistance rises with temperature.

429
00:31:29.590 --> 00:31:32.420
and the negative kind
where the resistance falls

430
00:31:32.420 --> 00:31:33.590
when the temperature goes up.

431
00:31:34.590 --> 00:31:36.630
So. like a thermometer?

432
00:31:36.630 --> 00:31:40.250
Um. no. like a circuit
that's reactive to temperature.

433
00:31:41.750 --> 00:31:43.630
- Like a thermometer?
- It's not a thermometer.

434
00:31:44.670 --> 00:31:46.080
What? Are you all science-y and shit?

435
00:31:46.090 --> 00:31:48.250
Well. I wouldn't say. "and shit."

436
00:31:48.250 --> 00:31:51.500
Take a lot of science.
prerequisite for vet school.

437
00:31:53.040 --> 00:31:53.880
Huh.

438
00:31:56.830 --> 00:31:57.830
Whoa.

439
00:32:01.880 --> 00:32:05.670
Hey! Wha-- what are you doing?

440
00:32:08.750 --> 00:32:10.340
That was fun. Oh. my God.

441
00:32:11.250 --> 00:32:12.920
Oh.

442
00:32:12.920 --> 00:32:14.340
Oh. cool!

443
00:32:18.380 --> 00:32:19.920
Yeah. this place was a...

444
00:32:20.590 --> 00:32:22.580
It was military storage
back in the day.

445
00:32:22.590 --> 00:32:24.130
weapons and what have you.

446
00:32:24.710 --> 00:32:26.960
They cleaned it out
and sold it a long time ago.

447
00:32:27.630 --> 00:32:32.630
Storage is only
on the ground floor and two sub-levels.

448
00:32:32.630 --> 00:32:34.420
But this lab
is what they care about.

449
00:32:34.420 --> 00:32:38.000
See the sensors?
They're all in bunches down here.

450
00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:40.880
- the lower sub-basements.
- "SB-4."

451
00:32:41.500 --> 00:32:44.590
You wanna go down and see it?

452
00:32:46.250 --> 00:32:47.250
No.

453
00:32:48.880 --> 00:32:50.170
How? I mean. they sealed it off.

454
00:32:51.130 --> 00:32:52.130
That.

455
00:32:53.380 --> 00:32:54.380
It's a tube ladder.

456
00:32:55.540 --> 00:32:58.500
- I'm not going down there.
- Oh. come on!

457
00:32:58.500 --> 00:33:00.710
This is. like. the most fun
I've had in years.

458
00:33:00.710 --> 00:33:03.000
This is like a night out for me.
This is great.

459
00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:04.130
Jesus.

460
00:33:05.250 --> 00:33:06.580
- That's depressing.
- Okay.

461
00:33:06.590 --> 00:33:07.790
What. you don't go out?

462
00:33:07.790 --> 00:33:10.040
Not really.

463
00:33:10.040 --> 00:33:11.710
What about for. like. a beer?

464
00:33:12.540 --> 00:33:13.540
I don't drink.

465
00:33:16.170 --> 00:33:17.170
Not even for one beer?

466
00:33:18.210 --> 00:33:19.750
That would be drinking.

467
00:33:26.710 --> 00:33:28.170
You know what?

468
00:33:28.170 --> 00:33:29.540
I thought you were fun. Teacake.

469
00:33:29.540 --> 00:33:31.170
- You started out fun.
- Who. me?

470
00:33:31.170 --> 00:33:32.710
Oh. I'm fun.

471
00:33:32.710 --> 00:33:34.170
Oh. I'm huge fun.

472
00:33:34.170 --> 00:33:35.880
You're the one who just said
your best night out in years

473
00:33:35.880 --> 00:33:37.540
is vandalizing your workplace.

474
00:33:37.540 --> 00:33:39.710
And that's cool. and I'm...
I'm. like. cooperating.

475
00:33:39.710 --> 00:33:41.080
You look at me with those eyes
you got that say.

476
00:33:41.090 --> 00:33:43.330
"Please. smash a hole in the wall."
I'm on board.

477
00:33:43.340 --> 00:33:46.540
And then you say. "Let's crawl
into this weird space and check it out."

478
00:33:46.540 --> 00:33:47.880
Still good. I'm into it.

479
00:33:47.880 --> 00:33:49.880
But then. you come at me. like.

480
00:33:49.880 --> 00:33:52.130
"Go crawl down the tube ladder
a couple hundred feet

481
00:33:52.130 --> 00:33:54.040
"into the blocked-off part
of the abandoned government shit

482
00:33:54.040 --> 00:33:56.130
"and see why the thermistor alarm
is going off."

483
00:33:56.130 --> 00:33:58.500
and a guy's just gotta
take a second to. like.

484
00:33:58.500 --> 00:34:00.500
think things through. you feel me?

485
00:34:01.790 --> 00:34:02.960
You like my eyes?

486
00:34:04.540 --> 00:34:06.130
Yeah. In fact. I do.

487
00:34:07.340 --> 00:34:11.380
- That's very sweet.
- My point is I'm kinda easy to...

488
00:34:12.290 --> 00:34:15.080
talk into things.
and that's why I got the problems I got.

489
00:34:15.090 --> 00:34:17.000
but I spend a lot of time
working on my personal shit.

490
00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:20.460
so I don't just walk into everything
that everybody asks me to do all the time.

491
00:34:20.460 --> 00:34:23.340
which is what I'm doing right now.
All right? I'm just taking a little...

492
00:34:24.130 --> 00:34:25.170
A moment.

493
00:34:26.960 --> 00:34:28.880
Okay.

494
00:34:29.500 --> 00:34:30.580
Word of advice.

495
00:34:30.580 --> 00:34:34.290
if a guy who goes by "Hazy Davy"
ever asks you to wait behind the wheel

496
00:34:34.290 --> 00:34:36.170
while he runs in the convenience store
real quick.

497
00:34:36.170 --> 00:34:39.290
you should for sure remember you got
something else to do right away. okay?

498
00:34:41.460 --> 00:34:42.630
I'm sorry.

499
00:34:43.290 --> 00:34:45.460
I... I was not being cool.

500
00:34:46.710 --> 00:34:48.580
That's more like it.

501
00:34:54.750 --> 00:34:56.000
You coming or what?

502
00:35:03.580 --> 00:35:05.630
You think that picture's
gonna cover that hole?

503
00:35:06.710 --> 00:35:07.710
Yeah. it'll be fine!

504
00:35:08.580 --> 00:35:09.580
Going down.

505
00:36:02.340 --> 00:36:03.920
Sub-level two.

506
00:36:08.210 --> 00:36:09.580
Okay.

507
00:36:13.210 --> 00:36:14.210
I think it's this way.

508
00:36:15.210 --> 00:36:16.710
What. some janitor's closet?

509
00:36:16.710 --> 00:36:18.340
That doesn't make sense.

510
00:36:21.790 --> 00:36:24.080
The only person who comes in here is Dave.
and he's a horrible janitor.

511
00:36:24.090 --> 00:36:25.420
so he's never in here.

512
00:36:25.420 --> 00:36:27.830
That's weird.
it's supposed to go 50 feet that way.

513
00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:31.290
Is that an outline?

